he first assumption relates to the predominant status of referential semantics and its power to explain truth-conditional meaning. This assumption has come under attack by the context thesis and a number of papers pursue the question of whether this is justified. The second assumption gives priority to assertive sentences when considering language use. The context thesis changes our understanding of language use altogether; possible implications from this methodological shift are addressed in this volume. According to the third assumption, philosophical analysis amounts to nothing more than conceptual analysis. The context thesis risks undermining this project. Whether conceptual analysis can still be defended as a methodological tool is discussed in this volume.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aContext (Linguistics) 0aContext (Linguistics). 0aContextualism (Philosophy). 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 0aSemantics. 4aPragmatik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Pragmatics.2bisacsh  aContext Thesis.  aContextualism.  aPhilosophy of Language.1 aAeschbacher, Dominik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBezuidenhout, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConrad, Sarah-Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConrad, Sarah-Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGauker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Damon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImhof, Silvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKompa, Nikola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorta, Kepa, econtributor.4ctb4https: